da and the US with respect to shared waters, as well as the implications of these changes for geopolitics and the environment. Water without Borders? is a timely publication given the increased attention to shared water issues, and particularly because 2013 is the United Nations International Year of Water Cooperation.Water without Borders? is designed to help readers develop a balanced understanding of the most pressing shared water issues between Canada and the United States. The contributors explore possible frictions between governance institutions and contemporary management issues, illustrated through analyses of five specific transboundary water “flashpoints.” The volume offers both a historical survey of transboundary governance mechanisms and a forward-looking assessment of new models of governance that will allow us to manage water wisely in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWater rightszCanada. 0aWater rightszUnited States. 0aWaterxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aWaterxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBakker, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakker, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBankes, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourget, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandson, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClamen, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Alice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, Noah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHearne, Rob